Effects of Time, User and Start Stations Factors on Bike Ride Durations.¶

by Elizabeth Ofulue¶

0.1. Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation, I want to look at the time, user and station factors of of bike rides that favor longer rides. The main focus is on the start day, start hour, start month, user type and start station.

Dataset Overview¶

The data consists of ride duration and attributes of approximately 519700 bike rides. The attributes of the data include the start time from which start day, hour and month for each ride were extracted, user type, start station id and name, as well as additional measurements such as end station id and name, start station latitude and longitude, end station latitude and longitude and end time.

0.2. Distribution of Ride Duration¶

The duration of bike rides take on large range of values from about \$67\$ at the lowest to \$67000\$ at the highest. With the presence of outliers which have been removed, the distribution of ride duration is plotted on a logarithmic scale. The plot takse the shape of a normal distribution.

0.3. Distribution of Start Hour¶

Using the 24 hout format, the start hour measures the exact hour a ride is taken. The values of the variable ranges from 01 t0 24, with 01 as the 1st representing 01:00 am and 24 as the 24th hour representing 00:00 am also known as midnight.

The distribution of the start hour variable is bimodal and slightly skewed to the left. Using the 24-hour format, most rides recorded occur between the 7th and 19th hour which is usually interpreted to be between 7:00am and 7:00pm. The 17th hour (5:00 pm) holds the most number of rides. There are no rides recorded for the 24th hour which is reasonable since this hour is usually interpreted as midnight.

0.4. Distribution of Start Month and Day¶

Start month and day represents the 12 month period and the 7 days of the week for each recorde bike ride. Both variables are ordered with start month ranging from January to December and start day ranging from Sunday to Saturday.

For start day, most of the rides are significantly centered around weekdays (Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday) compared to weekends (Saturday, Sunday). Of all the days, Tuesday is seen to have the most rides. For start month it can be seen that no rides were recorded for the month of January to May. However, rides were recorded from the month of June to December with October recording the highest number of rides.

0.6. Distribution of Top 10 Start Stations¶

The start stations indicates the location each bike ride started from. There are 272 unique stations in the dataset which cannot be plotted all at once. The top 10 start stations are therefore plotted instead. It is observed that the largest number of rides were taken at San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza).

0.7. Duration By User Type, Start Day, Hour and Month¶

Plotting duration on a logarithmic scale against each of the categorical variables (start day, hour, month and user type) produces insight into the variation of ride duration across variables. It can also be seen that the median ride duration was higher for Customers, and weekends (Saturday and Sunday). The median ride duration was also higher between 01:00am and 03:00am and almost equal for the months of July, August, September, October and November.

The difference in the ride duration during weekdays or weekends may be affected by the user type, start hour of start month of the ride. The effect of these categories across each other on the ride duration will be seen in the multivariate analysis.

0.8. Duration By Start Month and Day for Different Users¶

The plot communicates the hierachy in ride duration between customers and subscribers when measured against the start month, hour and day. It can be seen that customers took the longest rides in all months and days of the week compared to subscribers. Customers mostly took the longest rides in the month of July and on weekend (Saturday and Sunday). It can also be seen that customers take longer rides than subscribers and most customers took these rides mostly between 01: 00am to 05:00am.

1.0. Number of Rides by Top 10 Start Station Per User¶

From the plot above of the top 10 start stations, it is observed that the median duration of bike trips is longer for customers than subscribers. Customers tend to take longer rides compared to subscribers at the top 10 start stations. It is also observed that Customer rides were significantly longer that those of subscribers at the following start stations: San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza), The Embarcadero at Sansome St and `Montgomery St BART Station (Market St at 2nd St).
